      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA325-kiḷavi">itu tōḻi celavaḻuṅkuvittatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante prevented [HIM] from going.</p>
        </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA325">
<l>          kavitalai yeṇkiṉ parumayi rēṟṟai</l>
<l>          yiraitēr vēṭkaiyi ṉiraviṟ pōki</l>
<l>          nīṭuceyaṟ citalait tōṭupuṉain teṭutta</l>
<l>          varavāḻ puṟṟa moḻiya voyyeṉa</l>
<l>          muravāy vaḷḷuki riṭappa vāṅku</l>
<l>          mūkkaruṅ kavalai nīnti maṟṟivaḷ</l>
<l>          pūppō luṇkaṇ putunalañ citaiya</l>
<l>          vīṅkunīr vārak kaṇṭun</l>
<l>          takumō peruma tavirkanuñ celavē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Crossing<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nīnti māṟṟu</term>: actually we would expect this to be the subject of the <term xml:lang="ta">takumō</term>, but then it would have to be a verbal noun nīntal. Should we emend the text here or accept an anacoluthic construction (that can be moreover easily camouflaged in the English translation)?</note> the crossroad difficult to pass(?),</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the huge-furred male of the bear with overhanging head,</l>
<l rend="indent3">going at night in desire to search for prey,</l>
<l rend="indent2">bends to root up<note place="foot">Either this verb has to stay without direct object or we have to take <term xml:lang="ta">muravāy</term> as the "broken mound" of the anthill, not as an epithet of the nails.</note> with [its] sharp nails with broken tips,</l>
<l rend="indent">suddenly(?), so that the anthill, inhabited by a snake, is annihilated,</l>
<l rend="indent2">raised decoratively by the multitude of white ants in long action,</l>
<l>– is it fitting, o great one</l>
<l rend="indent">though having seen that swelling waters flow over,</l>
<l>so that the new beauty of her flower-like collyrium eyes is wasted?</l>
<l rend="indent4">Let your going be detained.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
